00:55:14.505 --> 00:55:15.380
Just raise your hand.

00:55:20.125 --> 00:55:21.500
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for the talk.

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:24.260
That was really interesting.

00:55:24.260 --> 00:55:26.830
So you emphasize that
most of your work

00:55:26.830 --> 00:55:30.600
focuses on people who have
learning disabilities.

00:55:30.600 --> 00:55:31.914
BARBARA ARROWSMITH-YOUNG: Mhm.

00:55:31.914 --> 00:55:33.580
AUDIENCE: Have you
tested this same kind

00:55:33.580 --> 00:55:38.870
of techniques on patients with
Alzheimer's or other sorts

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:41.190
of, you know, degenerative
diseases of the brain?

00:55:41.190 --> 00:55:41.660
BARBARA ARROWSMITH-YOUNG: No.

00:55:41.660 --> 00:55:44.159
That's a really good question,
and I think a lot about that.

00:55:44.159 --> 00:55:45.970
The answer is really
no, I haven't.

00:55:45.970 --> 00:55:48.920
My concern is if there's a
neurodegenerative process,

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:53.289
I don't believe we know enough
yet to be able to reverse that.

00:55:53.289 --> 00:55:54.830
There's certainly
research coming out

00:55:54.830 --> 00:55:58.530
that good cognitive
stimulation maybe can stave off

00:55:58.530 --> 00:56:00.551
the onset by a number of years.

00:56:00.551 --> 00:56:02.300
And there's a lot of
good research looking

00:56:02.300 --> 00:56:04.990
at people that have
dual language, which

00:56:04.990 --> 00:56:08.494
adds cognitive load,
cognitive complexity.

00:56:08.494 --> 00:56:10.910
And the research is suggesting
maybe it's five years later

00:56:10.910 --> 00:56:14.040
that they show the signs,
if they're going to get

00:56:14.040 --> 00:56:15.430
Alzheimer's.

00:56:15.430 --> 00:56:19.730
So I think good cognitive
stimulation is positive.

00:56:19.730 --> 00:56:21.730
I just don't think we
know enough at this point

00:56:21.730 --> 00:56:26.250
to say that it's
going to prevent that.

00:56:26.250 --> 00:56:28.430
AUDIENCE: Have you have you
come across any examples

00:56:28.430 --> 00:56:32.220
where a learning disability
has manifested itself

00:56:32.220 --> 00:56:35.885
as a learning superability
in some other context?

00:56:35.885 --> 00:56:37.260
BARBARA
ARROWSMITH-YOUNG: I have,

00:56:37.260 --> 00:56:39.480
and I mean, I've seen really
unevenness in profiles,

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:42.300
where somebody can be
exceptional in one area

00:56:42.300 --> 00:56:45.242
and have significant
difficulty in another.

00:56:48.540 --> 00:56:51.280
I mean, there is this
concept that I've

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:54.300
heard of there that there's
a gift of having a learning

00:56:54.300 --> 00:56:54.839
disability.

00:56:54.839 --> 00:56:57.380
I've talked to a lot of people
that have learning disability.

00:56:57.380 --> 00:57:00.110
Nobody considers that a gift.

00:57:00.110 --> 00:57:02.510
I mean, it doesn't
mean that maybe it

00:57:02.510 --> 00:57:05.480
teaches you, if you can, ways
to compensate and work around.

00:57:05.480 --> 00:57:08.760
But I myself do not
see the giftedness

00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:10.210
in having a learning disability.

00:57:10.210 --> 00:57:11.510
It's a struggle.

00:57:11.510 --> 00:57:14.170
It causes suffering.

00:57:14.170 --> 00:57:17.620
You just have to work so
much harder than everybody

00:57:17.620 --> 00:57:19.930
else to function.

00:57:19.930 --> 00:57:22.490
Now, I have seen
some students where

00:57:22.490 --> 00:57:25.320
because they have a difficulty
here, they have a strength

00:57:25.320 --> 00:57:28.369
here, and if they
rely on that strength

00:57:28.369 --> 00:57:29.910
over and over and
over again, they're

00:57:29.910 --> 00:57:31.760
probably creating their
own cognitive stimulation.

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:33.460
And they actually
improve that strength.

00:57:33.460 --> 00:57:35.550
It doesn't change the
learning difficulty.

00:57:35.550 --> 00:57:37.830
It improves the
strength that they have.

00:57:37.830 --> 00:57:40.470
I mean, for me, I
think I always had

00:57:40.470 --> 00:57:43.970
a good auditory
and visual memory,

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:45.050
but I supercharged them.

00:57:45.050 --> 00:57:48.080
I mean, my way of studying,
I'd lay my books out on my bed.

00:57:48.080 --> 00:57:51.090
As a child, I would cry from
the depths of my soul, which

00:57:51.090 --> 00:57:54.150
I was putting my brain
in kind of a Zen state,

00:57:54.150 --> 00:57:55.970
which I didn't know at the time.

00:57:55.970 --> 00:57:58.771
And then I would read the
first sentence, close my eyes,

00:57:58.771 --> 00:58:01.020
see it, read the next sentence,
close my eyes, see it.

00:58:01.020 --> 00:58:02.460
By the end, I could look
at the first sentence.

00:58:02.460 --> 00:58:03.876
I could close my
eyes, and I could

00:58:03.876 --> 00:58:06.970
see 50 pages of my notebook.

00:58:06.970 --> 00:58:08.760
I had a good ability there.

00:58:08.760 --> 00:58:12.990
I think I enhanced that ability
through using it all the time

00:58:12.990 --> 00:58:15.141
and over-using it.

00:58:15.141 --> 00:58:16.640
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks
for being here.

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:20.250
I was just wondering, even
in your personal example,

00:58:20.250 --> 00:58:22.540
like you go through these
training curriculums,

00:58:22.540 --> 00:58:26.160
and you try to identify the
problem and find a solution.

00:58:26.160 --> 00:58:29.500
After the person kind
of enhances that ability

00:58:29.500 --> 00:58:31.599
wherever they were
weak, is there

00:58:31.599 --> 00:58:33.390
something they have to
do to continue that?

00:58:33.390 --> 00:58:35.230
Or is it kind of like
if you don't use it,

00:58:35.230 --> 00:58:36.490
you lose it, kind of thing?

00:58:36.490 --> 00:58:38.020
BARBARA ARROWSMITH YOUNG:
Interestingly what we see,

00:58:38.020 --> 00:58:39.603
because that's a
really good question,

00:58:39.603 --> 00:58:41.160
is there's no drop off.

00:58:41.160 --> 00:58:44.200
I've tracked myself and other
people of over 30 years out

00:58:44.200 --> 00:58:45.024
of the program.

00:58:45.024 --> 00:58:46.440
And I think why--
because, I mean,

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:49.400
we know if we stop going to
gym, our muscles atrophy.

00:58:49.400 --> 00:58:51.035
But I think what
happens is if we think

00:58:51.035 --> 00:58:53.410
about that functional system,
like all these areas coming

00:58:53.410 --> 00:58:56.140
together in a neural network,
if there's some weak areas,

00:58:56.140 --> 00:58:58.850
they're acting as a drag
on that whole system.

00:58:58.850 --> 00:59:02.020
Once you see you improve them,
enhance them, they come up.

00:59:02.020 --> 00:59:04.590
And then they get
their own stimulation

00:59:04.590 --> 00:59:07.490
by being engaged in
that neural network.

00:59:07.490 --> 00:59:08.692
That's my theory.

00:59:08.692 --> 00:59:10.030
It make sense to me.

00:59:10.030 --> 00:59:14.220
Practically, what I see is
once they've achieved the gain,

00:59:14.220 --> 00:59:15.590
there's no drop off in function.

00:59:15.590 --> 00:59:18.180
Because I believe they're
starting to use it

00:59:18.180 --> 00:59:20.645
in everyday functioning.

00:59:20.645 --> 00:59:23.020
AUDIENCE: Have you noticed an
difference between children

00:59:23.020 --> 00:59:25.480
and adults or how
neuroplasticity

00:59:25.480 --> 00:59:26.400
changes with age?

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:28.500
BARBARA ARROWSMITH-YOUNG: Yeah,
when I first started this work,

00:59:28.500 --> 00:59:29.666
there was all this research.

00:59:29.666 --> 00:59:31.670
There's this beautiful
window of neuroplasticity

00:59:31.670 --> 00:59:33.280
that starts to close at age 12.

00:59:33.280 --> 00:59:36.950
And you know, it's kind
of all over at age 12.

00:59:36.950 --> 00:59:39.480
So I thought I would
see a big difference

00:59:39.480 --> 00:59:45.380
in the rate of progress in
children versus adolescents,

00:59:45.380 --> 00:59:47.010
adults, young adults.

00:59:47.010 --> 00:59:48.240
I haven't seen that.

00:59:48.240 --> 00:59:52.020
It really was probably the
biggest surprise that I found.

00:59:52.020 --> 00:59:55.360
I've seen variability in
plasticity, which makes sense.

00:59:55.360 --> 00:59:57.280
There's individual
variability in everything.

00:59:57.280 --> 00:59:59.590
And there's a lot of research
now looking at genetics,

00:59:59.590 --> 01:00:03.260
looking at what goes into
different rates of plasticity.

01:00:03.260 --> 01:00:05.160
I mean, I've got lots
of examples in my work

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:06.600
where two people come in.

01:00:06.600 --> 01:00:10.140
They look very similar in the
profile, same gender, same age,

01:00:10.140 --> 01:00:11.710
do the same amount of work.

01:00:11.710 --> 01:00:14.615
They both make progress, but
one goes four times faster

01:00:14.615 --> 01:00:15.240
than the other.

01:00:15.240 --> 01:00:19.030
And there's probably just more
plasticity in that individual.

01:00:19.030 --> 01:00:24.499
But I think about the
74-year-old retired professor

01:00:24.499 --> 01:00:26.540
from the medical school
at University of Toronto.

01:00:26.540 --> 01:00:27.090
She came in.

01:00:27.090 --> 01:00:28.120
She had face blindness.

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:29.900
It had always bothered
her, worked on it.

01:00:29.900 --> 01:00:32.140
She made the same
progress as a 15-year-old.

01:00:32.140 --> 01:00:35.010
So to me, as I'm getting
older, it's really encouraging.

01:00:35.010 --> 01:00:39.250
There's neuroplasticity
over the lifespan.

