01:03:14.030 --> 01:03:16.760
But incredible struggle.

01:03:16.760 --> 01:03:20.659
In my undergraduate, I learned
the routines of the security

01:03:20.659 --> 01:03:22.200
guards in the library
because I would

01:03:22.200 --> 01:03:23.500
spend all night in the library.

01:03:23.500 --> 01:03:27.280
So I would know when they were
coming to do their walkabout.

01:03:27.280 --> 01:03:29.040
I would hide out
in the washroom.

01:03:29.040 --> 01:03:35.770
I worked seven days a week,
20 hours every single day

01:03:35.770 --> 01:03:36.734
just to tread water.

01:03:36.734 --> 01:03:37.900
I mean, that's what it took.

01:03:37.900 --> 01:03:39.910
Because I wasn't
understanding conceptually.

01:03:39.910 --> 01:03:44.220
I was having to rely on memory,
which is really brute force.

01:03:44.220 --> 01:03:45.676
I compromised my immune system.

01:03:45.676 --> 01:03:47.050
I have an immune
system disorder.

01:03:47.050 --> 01:03:48.470
There's a lot of
research now looking

01:03:48.470 --> 01:03:50.553
into the field of learning
disabilities and seeing

01:03:50.553 --> 01:03:51.220
a connection.

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:58.180
It's all the stressors that
affect your endocrine system.

01:03:58.180 --> 01:04:00.460
So it wasn't just a
learning disability.

01:04:00.460 --> 01:04:03.010
It affected all sorts
of things in my life.

01:04:03.010 --> 01:04:06.280
And just before I came
across the book that

01:04:06.280 --> 01:04:09.430
was given to me-- when I
was 13, I attempted suicide.

01:04:09.430 --> 01:04:10.740
It wasn't successful.

01:04:10.740 --> 01:04:12.680
It was kind of that
two-edged sword--

01:04:12.680 --> 01:04:14.730
the despair of having
a learning difficulty,

01:04:14.730 --> 01:04:16.476
thinking I've got to
go to high school.

01:04:16.476 --> 01:04:18.350
I could barely get
through elementary school.

01:04:18.350 --> 01:04:20.220
How can I do this?

01:04:20.220 --> 01:04:22.681
So that despair led me
to try to end my life.

01:04:22.681 --> 01:04:24.680
But my learning disability
meant I didn't really

01:04:24.680 --> 01:04:26.790
understand the instructions
of how you did that.

01:04:26.790 --> 01:04:29.370
And I can laugh at it now.

01:04:29.370 --> 01:04:30.389
So I wasn't successful.

01:04:30.389 --> 01:04:32.430
But when I woke up the
next morning, as I thought

01:04:32.430 --> 01:04:33.040
you did something.

01:04:33.040 --> 01:04:33.710
You went to bed.

01:04:33.710 --> 01:04:34.957
You just didn't wake up.

01:04:34.957 --> 01:04:36.415
When I woke up the
next morning, it

01:04:36.415 --> 01:04:38.190
was another opportunity
to attack myself,

01:04:38.190 --> 01:04:40.000
like I just couldn't
even get that right.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:43.470
But just before I
came across this work,

01:04:43.470 --> 01:04:45.310
this time I was planning again.

01:04:45.310 --> 01:04:47.101
And this time I would
have gotten it right,

01:04:47.101 --> 01:04:48.910
because I knew what I had to do.

01:04:48.910 --> 01:04:53.300
So that's why I feel like I
owe a life debt to Luria's work

01:04:53.300 --> 01:04:56.167
because that turned
my life around.

01:04:56.167 --> 01:04:57.000
There was no future.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:02.510
Yes, I was in graduate school,
maybe I would have got through.

01:05:02.510 --> 01:05:04.300
I'm not sure whether
I would've or not.

01:05:07.700 --> 01:05:09.220
There was no life.

01:05:09.220 --> 01:05:11.970
I didn't have relationships.

01:05:11.970 --> 01:05:15.430
If I got on an elevator
in my university

01:05:15.430 --> 01:05:17.130
and one of my
professors got on, I

01:05:17.130 --> 01:05:19.420
was terrified that they
would ask me a question

01:05:19.420 --> 01:05:21.916
because I wouldn't understand
what they were asking

01:05:21.916 --> 01:05:23.920
and be able to have
a conversation.

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:27.020
Like, I lived in
terror all the time.

01:05:30.954 --> 01:05:33.120
AUDIENCE: Just kind of, I
guess in all your research

01:05:33.120 --> 01:05:35.800
and with working with so
many different clients,

01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:37.640
any tips that you
would provide just

01:05:37.640 --> 01:05:40.237
in general for the overall
cognitive well-being?

01:05:40.237 --> 01:05:41.570
BARBARA ARROWSMITH-YOUNG: A few.

01:05:41.570 --> 01:05:43.990
I do have slides in here,
but I didn't get to them.

01:05:43.990 --> 01:05:47.430
One of the best
things you can do--

01:05:47.430 --> 01:05:49.440
exercise, aerobic exercise.

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:51.140
There's tons of research now.

01:05:51.140 --> 01:05:52.610
I know you've got bikes here.

01:05:52.610 --> 01:05:54.080
You've got walking trails.

01:05:54.080 --> 01:05:57.630
It doesn't have to
be more than go out

01:05:57.630 --> 01:06:01.950
and walk 30 minutes a day,
a good, nice, brisk walk.

01:06:01.950 --> 01:06:03.620
Aerobic exercise,
the rule is kind

01:06:03.620 --> 01:06:04.786
of it's good for your heart.

01:06:04.786 --> 01:06:06.060
It's good for your brain.

01:06:06.060 --> 01:06:07.610
It stimulates.

01:06:07.610 --> 01:06:10.600
It's called BDNF-- brain
derived neurotrophic factor.

01:06:10.600 --> 01:06:16.240
And that generates neurogenesis,
creating new neurons.

01:06:16.240 --> 01:06:20.140
Also it repair cells,
like all that damage

01:06:20.140 --> 01:06:21.244
that happens over time.

01:06:21.244 --> 01:06:23.160
So if you can only do
one thing, get out there

01:06:23.160 --> 01:06:28.050
and at least five days a
week do some good exercise.

01:06:28.050 --> 01:06:30.180
Another thing, reduce stress.

01:06:30.180 --> 01:06:33.010
I mean, all the
research is showing now

01:06:33.010 --> 01:06:35.810
that stress actually is
almost like an acid bath

01:06:35.810 --> 01:06:36.480
for your brain.

01:06:36.480 --> 01:06:38.370
I mean, short term
stress, not a problem.

01:06:38.370 --> 01:06:41.210
It's that long term
chronic stress,

01:06:41.210 --> 01:06:46.367
which actually creates
negative neuroplasticity.

01:06:46.367 --> 01:06:48.200
When those dendrites
are starting to branch,

01:06:48.200 --> 01:06:51.080
it actually eats
up the dendrites.

01:06:51.080 --> 01:06:55.355
So anything, whether
it's meditation, again,

01:06:55.355 --> 01:06:56.480
sometimes going for a walk.

01:06:56.480 --> 01:06:59.580
Whatever you can do to
reduce stress in your life

01:06:59.580 --> 01:07:01.550
is good for brain health.

01:07:01.550 --> 01:07:04.420
Whatever you can do to
increase aerobic activity

01:07:04.420 --> 01:07:05.850
is good for brain health.

01:07:05.850 --> 01:07:10.330
And then the other thing is
sort of novelty and cognitive

01:07:10.330 --> 01:07:12.490
complexity, which I
talked a little bit about.

01:07:12.490 --> 01:07:14.840
So let's say you want
to learn something new.

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:21.650
What you should do is calibrate
the level of the challenge.

01:07:21.650 --> 01:07:24.920
So let's say you
want to learn chess.

01:07:24.920 --> 01:07:27.500
But you're not going to start
at the grandmaster level.

01:07:27.500 --> 01:07:29.875
Because if you do, like let's
say you're functioning here

01:07:29.875 --> 01:07:32.297
and you try to start the
activity way up here,

01:07:32.297 --> 01:07:33.880
you aren't going to
be able to engage.

01:07:33.880 --> 01:07:35.780
It's not going to drive
neuroplastic change.

01:07:35.780 --> 01:07:38.240
If you make it so easy,
as your brain goes

01:07:38.240 --> 01:07:40.312
on automatic pilot--
I mean, there's

01:07:40.312 --> 01:07:42.520
lots of times when you want
to be on automatic pilot.

01:07:42.520 --> 01:07:44.820
But if you're trying to
drive neuroplastic change,

01:07:44.820 --> 01:07:46.550
automatic pilot doesn't do it.

01:07:46.550 --> 01:07:48.370
So if you're making
something too simple,

01:07:48.370 --> 01:07:49.600
it's not engaging the brain.

01:07:49.600 --> 01:07:51.266
So it's kind of finding
that sweet spot,

01:07:51.266 --> 01:07:53.093
just like in exercise.

01:07:53.093 --> 01:07:57.380
If this is where it starts
to hurt a little bit,

01:07:57.380 --> 01:08:00.150
make it just a little
bit more difficult.

01:08:00.150 --> 01:08:02.320
Then do the activity,
and then you'll

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:03.552
find it'll little step up.

01:08:03.552 --> 01:08:05.260
And then make it a
little more difficult.

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:08.690
It's calibrating the
level of complexity.

01:08:08.690 --> 01:08:10.960
And you can do that
in any activity

01:08:10.960 --> 01:08:11.960
that you're engaging in.

01:08:11.960 --> 01:08:16.020
And that will be the best thing
to drive neuroplastic change.

01:08:16.020 --> 01:08:19.170
So exercise, reduce stress,
and calibrate the level

01:08:19.170 --> 01:08:21.119
of difficulty in your learning.

